@Node "Introduction" "PhotoFolio.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Getting_started"
@Prev "Main"

@Smartwrap

@{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

	PhotoFolio is designed to be used by anyone wishing to view, store or
catalogue images. It will run on any Commodore-Amiga (020 and above)
computer running Kickstart 3.0 or higher.


Its features include:

	· PhotoFolio is shareware and completely UNRESTRICTED.


	· Fully user configurable generation of proofs.


	· Amiga User Interface Style Guide compliant user interface (I believe)
using MUI.


	· Displaying of images including scaled image loading.


	· Cataloguing of images into owners (255), groups (4) and categories (22).


	· Selective display of catalogued proofs, using 3 different boolean
operations.


	· Copying, deleting and saving of images and proofs.


	· Automatic gamma correction of proofs.


	· 3 different modes of image scaling.


	· 3 different sort modes for proofs (alphabetical, size, type).


	· PhotoAlbum compatability (JPEG thumbnails only).


	· Any number of browse windows can be opened at once (limited by system
memory).


	· Online help.


	· Progressive image loading.


	· Datatype support.


	· CyberGraphX support.


	· Will work on any native Amiga display mode.


	· VLab support.


	· External viewer support.


	· English, Spanish, Italian, German, French and Czech translations available.


@{b}@{u}Overview@{ub}@{uu}

	PhotoFolio uses proof.library to create proofs. These are then stored on
disk for later use. On average a proof that is about 85x85 pixels in size
takes up about 2-3k of disk space. This makes the program very efficient
when it comes to both speed and storage.


	Proofs can be stored with the original image in which case the proof is
given a different name (non-linked), or the proof can be stored in a
mirrored directory structure in which case it maintains the same name as
the original image (linked).

@EndNode

@Node "Getting_started" "PhotoFolio.guide/Gettng_started"
@Next "FAQ"
@Prev "Introduction"

@Smartwrap

@{b}@{u}How to use PhotoFolio - A quick guide@{ub}@{uu}


When PhotoFolio is run, the @{"main window" Link "Main_window"} will open containing a listtree.
This listtree is used to contain any numbers of paths that you may want to
view. When the mouse is over the listtree you can use the right mouse
button to bring up a context menu of different choices, use "Add one path",
or "Add all paths", or "Add all paths recursively" to add paths to the
listtree.


Once you have added your paths to the listtree, you can view them by either:

1) Double clicking the path

2) Hold the mouse over the required path and select "Open in new window"
from the context menu

3) Select "New browse..." from the main menu and then drag the path into
that window.


When this is done, a @{"browse window" Link "Browse_window"} will open.
This window is used to browse through your proofs. From here you can show
them full size, categorise them, sort them, move them, copy them, even
delete them.


If the path you have selected contains images, then the loading of the
@{"browse window" Link "Browse_window"} will be slow, because PhotoFolio has to load them, then scale
them, then store them as proofs. Once this is done you can save the proofs.
The next time you want to view this path, simply load the path containing
the proofs and they will load very quickly.


If you run low on memory and can't load all the proofs, PhotoFolio will
stop loading and display a set of gadgets at the bottom of the @{"browse window" Link "Browse_window"},
allowing you to step back and forward through pages of proofs.


When you save proofs, they will be saved to the path that is stored in
"Settings/Make/Proof Destination Directory". Next time you wish to view
these images, don't load the image path, load the proof path. The proofs
contain a link to the original image and you can then perform all the
operations on the proof as if it was the original image. Loading now will
be a lot faster.


If you have a lot of images to browse, it is better to make them before
opening a @{"browse window" Link "Browse_window"}. To do this, hold the mouse over the path you want
to make and then select "Make path..." from the context menu. Or, select
"Make all paths..." from the context menu to make them all. A @{"make window" Link "Make_window"} 
will open, from here you can set all your parameters and default categories
and then start making. This is quicker than opening a @{"browse window" Link "Browse_window"} because
PhotoFolio doesn't have to display the proofs. When the image path is made,
the path the proofs are stored in is added to the "Temp path" node in the
listtree. You can open this path to view the proofs.


@EndNode

@Node "FAQ" "PhotoFolio.guide/FAQ"
@Next "Shareware"
@Prev "Getting_started"

@Smartwrap

@{b}@{u}Frequently Asked Questions@{ub}@{uu}


@{b}@{i}I have loaded my image path and saved the proofs, however the next
time I load them, it is no faster, why?@{ub}@{ui}


Once you have saved your proofs to disk, you should then load the proofs,
not the images. If you load the images again, PhotoFolio has to do all the
hard work of scaling etc again. However by selecting the proof directory,
PhotoFolio can load the proofs directly and it is lightning fast!!


@{b}@{i}When PhotoFolio updates the browse window it seems very slow, why?@{ub}@{ui}


The image of a proof is stored as a jpeg in the proof file. This means the
proof files can remain very small and don't take up much disk space.
However as a trade off to this, the jpeg has to be decoded before it can be
displayed. Decoding of jpegs is slow (unless you have a PPC card :-). If
you have your proof update setting set to a high number (say 70 - 100), it
will seem to take a long time to update the browse window, in reality it is
probably quicker than if it was set to a low number (say 5 - 10). The speed
is a trade off against proof size.

@EndNode

